        <body>
           <div type="edition" subtype="ogham" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl" resp="#NW">
            <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl" resp="#NW">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/>MOINENA MAQI OLACON
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app n="1">
                        <note><q>The fracture crosses E3, in consequence of which this letter has previously been read U</q> (Macalister 1945, 143). There is no trace of a final -A in the father's name.</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>Of M son of Olchú</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>This is one of the inscriptions listed by McManus (1991, 94) in which apocope (loss of final consonants or syllables) begins to show itself (MOINENA (earlier -AS), OLACON (earlier -AS)). This suggests that it may be dated to the first half of the sixth century (McManus 1991, 97).</p>
                <p>The persosnal name OLACON(AS) is a compound of OL-, possibly OIr. <foreign xml:lang="ga"><ref target="https://dil.ie/33804">oll</ref></foreign> 'great, ample' (ogham L can represent L or LL), and -CONAS 'dog, hound, wolf' (McManus 1991, 102, 177 (n.7))</p>
            </div>
